08578a745a5b92349", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "curl -L --max-time 20 -s https://api.github.com/repos/sksamuel/hoplite/contents | python3 - <<'PY'\nimport sys,json\ntry:\n data=json.load(sys.stdin)\n print('\\n'.join(x['name'] for x in data if 'hoplite' in x['name'].lower() or x['name'] in ['build.gradle.kts','README.md']))\nexcept Exception as e: print(e)\nPY", "timeout": 25}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 3250, "output": 254, "cacheRead": 25600, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 29104, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1782619939176, "responseId": "resp_0857287a4f991080016a409f23e6c88190b0dd8fb4e3a772bc"}, "toolResults": [{"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_ohRe8hsWeKLKNEpwJHOBOf2a|fc_0857287a4f991080016a409f26b7f8819090052870f3715a50", "toolName": "bash", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "196:## Supported Formats\n197-\n198-Hoplite supports config files in several formats. You can mix and match formats if you really want to.\n199-For each format you wish to use, you must include the appropriate hoplite module on your classpath.\n200-The format that hoplite uses to parse a file is determined by the file extension.\n201-\n202-| Format                                                              | Module                                                             | File Extensions     |\n203-|:--------------------------------------------------------------------|:-------------------------------------------------------------------|:--------------------|\n204-| [Json](https://www.json.org/)                                       | [`hoplite-json`](https://search.maven.org/search?q=hoplite-json)   | .json               |\n205-| [Yaml](https://yaml.org/) Note: Yaml files are limited 3mb in size. | [`hoplite-yaml`](https://search.maven.org/search?q=hoplite-yaml)   | .yml, .yaml         |\n206-| [Toml](https://github.com/toml-lang/toml)                           | [`hoplite-toml`](https://search.maven.org/search?q=hoplite-toml)   | .toml               |\n207-| [Hocon](https://github.com/lightbend/config)                        | [`hoplite-hocon`](https://search.maven.org/search?q=hoplite-hocon) | .conf               |\n208-| Java Properties files                                               | built-in                                                           | .props, .properties |\n209-\n210-If you wish to add another format you can extend `Parser` and provide an instance of that implementation to\n211-the `ConfigLoaderBuilder` via `addParser`.\n212-\n213-That same function can be used to map non-default file extensions to an existing parser. For example, if you wish to\n214-have your config in files called `application.data` but in yaml format, then you can register .data with the Yaml parser\n215-like this:\n216-\n217-`ConfigLoaderBuilder.default().addParser(\"data\", YamlParser).build()`\n218-\n219-### Note: fatJar/shadowJar\n220-\n221-If attempting to build a \"fat Jar\" while using multiple file type modules, it is essential to use [the shadowJar plugin](https://imperceptiblethoughts.com/shadow/) and to add the directive `mergeServiceFiles()` in the shadowJar Gradle task. [More info](https://imperceptiblethoughts.com/shadow/configuration/merging/#merging-service-descriptor-files)\n222-\n223-## Property Sources\n224-\n225-The `PropertySource` interface is how Hoplite reads configuration values.\n226-\n227-Hoplite supports several built in property source implementations, and you can write your own if required.\n228-\n229-The `EnvironmentVariablesPropertySource`, `SystemPropertiesPropertySource`, `UserSettingsPropertySource`, and `XdgConfigPropertySource`\n230-sources are automatically registered, with precedence in that order. Other property sources can be passed to the config loader builder\n231-as required.\n232-\n233-\n234-\n235-### EnvironmentVariablesPropertySource\n236-\n237-The `EnvironmentVariablesPropertySource` reads config from environment variables.\n238-This property source maps environment variable names to config properties via idiomatic conventions for environment variables.\n239-Env vars are idiomatically UPPERCASE and [contain only](https://pubs.opengroup.org/onlinepubs/000095399/basedefs/xbd_chap08.html) letters (`A` to `Z`), digits (`0` to `9`), and the underscore (`_`) character.\n240-\n241-Hoplite's binding rules align with [Spring Boot's relaxed binding for environment variables](https://docs.spring.io/spring-boot/reference/features/external-config.html#features.external-config.typesafe-configuration-properties.relaxed-binding.environment-variables) so that the same env vars can drive both kinds of app:\n242-\n243-| Rule | Env var | Binds to |\n244-|------|---------|----------|\n245-| Dots in property paths become underscores | `TOPIC_NAME` | `topic.name` |\n246-| Matching is case-insensitive — env vars uppercase, fields can be camelCase | `SPRING_MAIN_LOGSTARTUPINFO` | `spring.main.logStartupInfo` |\n247-| Dashes in property paths are removed (not replaced with underscores) | `LOGSTARTUPINFO` | `log-startup-info` (e.g. via `@ConfigAlias`) |\n248-| List/array indices are surrounded by underscores | `ITEMS_0`, `ITEMS_1` | `items: List<String>` |\n249-| List of nested objects | `SERVICE_0_OTHER`, `SERVICE_1_OTHER` | `service: List<Service(other = ...)>` |\n250-| Trailing path segment names a map key | `LABELS_ENV`, `LABELS_REGION` | `labels: Map<String, String>` |\n251-\n252-* Missing list indices are ignored, which is useful for commenting out values without renumbering subsequent ones.\n253-\n254-* **Map keys preserve case from the env var name.** Spring lowercases map keys (so `VALUES_KEY=v` produces `{\"key\": \"v\"}`); hoplite keeps them verbatim (`{\"KEY\": \"v\"}`). This is the one documented difference from Spring's rules and is locked in by `EnvironmentVariablesPropertySourceTest > build env source can create case sensitive Maps`.\n255-\n256-If the optional (not specified by default) `prefix` setting is provided, then only env vars that begin with the prefix are considered,\n257-and the prefix is stripped from the env var before processing.\n258-\n259-As of Hoplite 3, the `EnvironmentVariablesPropertySource` is applied by default and may be used to override other config properties\n260-directly. There is no longer any built-in support for the `config.override.` prefix. However, the optional `prefix` setting can still\n261-be used for the same purpose.\n262-\n263-\n264-### SystemPropertiesPropertySource\n265-\n266-The `SystemPropertiesPropertySource` provides config through system properties that are prefixed with `config.override.`.\n267-For example, starting your JVM with `-Dconfig.override.database.name` would override a config key of `database.name` residing in a file.\n268-\n269-The prefix may be customized by passing a `prefix` argument to the constructor, or set to an empty string to expose\n270-all system properties.\n271-\n272-\n273-### UserSettingsPropertySource\n274-\n275-The `UserSettingsPropertySource` provides config through a config file defined at ~/.userconfig.[ext] where ext is one of the [supported formats](#supported-formats).\n276-\n"}], "isError": false, "timestamp": 1782619943133}, {"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_bCczxbujnWsDXJxhzETd7hFe|fc_0857287a4f991080016a409f26b8088190a61f6edc4a8a60dc", "toolName": "bash", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "# Changelog\n\n### 3.0.0\n\n* Breaking: the `EnvironmentVariablesPropertySource` now uses idiomatic environment variable format i.e. upper case (though lower\ncase is still accepted), letters, and digits. **Single underscores** now separate path hierarchies.\n* Breaking: The `EnvironmentVariableOverridePropertySource` has been removed. The standard `EnvironmentVariablesPropertySource` is now\nloaded by default, and takes precedence over other default sources just like the `Envi